segments.text: with the Texas Department of Community Affairs is Larry Crumpton.
Larry was one of the early staffers, right after Shanahan probably left or right around in there, worked in housing.
And now he's a deputy over at Texas Department of Community Affairs.
But Larry has been over there for a number of years and could describe for you, probably in more detail,
actually that certification process.
But that certification process, if I remember correctly, was sort of instituted around 72, maybe 73.
And it was the official certification of planners.
And in order to obtain any of the local planning assistance, you had to be certified and to assure that you did quality work.
So I'll have to yield to either Larry over there.
There were several other people that worked around with this.
Charles Englishby is one staff person, I think, over at TDCA that you might ask about that.
Another question.
Would you describe the Texas 2000 program a bit, and what that was supposed to achieve, and who the guiding lights were, and why it was awarded to the LBJ School of Public Affairs?
Or would you, I don't know if you were close to that program or not, Leon.
OK. OK, let me try to.
pass on as best I can some of the history of that.
And this is trying to dredge up a little bit because I never was actually one of the key participants in it.
As I understand it, as Governor Briscoe was involved in announcing his State of the State in 1979,
he did indicate that there needed to be a created Texas 2000 type project to project to the year 2000 what we were going to be faced with.
That's Governor Briscoe.
My understanding was that it was a brainchild of someone over at the University of Texas, and I can't really identify the key people
that might have brought that up at that time.
I think it might have been the chap from Philadelphia who has since left the faculty.
Well, I'm not sure.
I do know that there were several.
Granowski has been mentioned as a person that's been involved in the thinking of some of that.
Walt Rostow has been mentioned as a person that was very interested in some of this.
Walt, I think, has done a lot of work in water issues and water problems.
So I don't know exactly who might have generated it to Governor Briscoe, but it was mentioned.
In fact, Governor Briscoe made sure that people remembered that, hey, I mentioned this.
But it was really, I guess, Governor Clements that, through his work,
you know, drilling company experience of being able to, you know, the one thing about Governor Clements was that you talk about short and mid-range planning, it was sort of a waste of time.

But, you know, when you start talking about long-range planning, his eyes lit up because he clearly was appalled at the amount of data and information that the state government had and trying to recognize our position in the world affairs
and he was extremely concerned about what we would need to be doing in order to deal with the year 2000 and beyond.
And I think that was one of the key things that Governor Clements did, is that he felt so strongly about that that he pushed extremely hard on the Texas 2000 project.
Early, fairly early in his administration, and I have to draw some dates to kind of,
benchmark it, but came into office in 69.
I think it was really probably in the spring of 70 by the time we began recognizing the governor really wanted to do something in this and began pushing on it.
Dr. Vic Arnold out of the LBJ school was brought over on a part-time basis initially.
And then shortly thereafter, some period of time thereafter, it was a deal cut and so forth, and Vic was brought over full time.
Vic was from Minneapolis, wasn't he?
I believe so, as a planning director in Minnesota.
And had pulled off several planning initiatives that were similar, not just like it, but similar kinds of activities.
a projections program, that kind of thing.
And Vic was a very articulate, or is a very articulate guy.
And you might, let me.
But the Texas 2000 project, Vic Arnold, part of the, quote, keystones of that was that we were going to have state agencies, loan staff,
to assist Vic and to pull off the project.
That's the way it started.
I had the Texas Advisory Commission on Intergovernmental Relations loaned a staff person almost full time.
The comptroller, the general land office were all people.
Bob Armstrong, at the time, was interested, of course, in that type project.
And a number of people.
There was a conference here on it at the Thompson Center, as I recall.
There was initially, they began trying to structure the project.
Ultimately, there was a Texas 2000 commission formed.
And the commission members were blue ribbon type private sector people, as well as key people like Senator Jones from the legislature, Senate finance chairman.
And it was a very strong blue ribbon type group.
There are still staff people around that worked on that.

Vic Arnold, by the way, has since gone to the University of Texas Bureau of Business Research, heads up that particular entity, and would be very interested in explaining the good things that did occur there.
As, again, I mentioned, he's very articulate, was able to work through bureaucracy very well,
wrote well, and did some good work.
In fact, there are some still pieces of his work that I'm sure he's still involved with over at Bureau of Business Research, because he's still very interested.
We have little components of Texas 2000 still a part of our office.
The data program that was sort of instituted
working with Bureau of Census and trying to do some projections.
And so some of that is still a part of our office.
And it was really some of that Texas 2000.
In order to do much projections, you've got to have a database.
And I think the database development and things like that are things that we're still struggling with trying to get a handle on that.
Speaking of that, we understand that there are several state agencies that have made population and economic projections
and that there is no one forecast or series of projections that the state uses.
Would you like to comment on that state of affairs, for example, on water resources and so forth?
There are a number of state agencies that do population projections.
And primarily, they do it for their purposes.
always look at the projections and see that the highway department is going to have a set, the water resource is going to have a set, the health department has a set.
They tend to try to prove either that they need a whole lot of additional whatevers or the fact that the problems aren't that great, depending on where they stand.
It is a very political issue.
Governor Briscoe got killed.
early on in his administration, 1973 or late in 73 or 74, wound up being in some little town in South Texas and making a speech.
And he just, we just released a set of the population projections.
And it essentially said that little town was not going to exist in five years.
And I tell you there, you know, subsequent, you could not bring that up to that administration.
Population projection was a no-no.
It was ultimately the demise.
At that time, we had a governor's office of information services.
Over 100 employees working with trying to develop compatibility of computers among state agencies and dealing with a lot of different issues and database.
Essentially, that agency was eliminated shortly thereafter.
Over 100 employees.
passed away.
And so there really has not been an official set of projections since that time.
There were some efforts under Governor Clements to develop into some projections.
We never really reached an ultimate set that everybody used.
It continues to be something that, of course,
When you have a census like 1980 census, at least you have a benchmark.
From 70, our data was real weak by the time you got to 78, 79.
There are several things you talk about here.
You talk about projections, but you also talk about estimates.
Because until you have the decennial census, you're flapping around out there trying to make some real
unprofessional judgments.
Well, we're going to be saved by the new 1985 census, which will just be a head count, just an enumeration.
But at least it will give us a midpoint benchmark.
We have on the agenda of trying to move into the projections area, we realize that it still is a political issue.
But having at least our office is established as the data center.
And we do get the most up-to-date information from the Bureau of Census at a national level.
We are trying to even make better use of the products that we get out of the census and different analysis of that data.
Right now, we're doing a little innovative project that's not a real pure planning project, but you've got to have data.
I think that's one of the key things that we're trying to work on right now, is that we have recently provided a microcomputer to each of the 24 COGs.
It was an effort to try to at least provide both a technical link but also a philosophical link between the regional planning commissions in our office

We are beginning to try to use that linkage between our office to share on our little floppy disk different kinds of data sets for each region, both in terms of information from the census department, but also information that we can gen up A&M,
There's a department over A&M is actually our technical expertise on the data center.
Are you all familiar with that?
Probably rural sociology.
Murdoch?
Steve Murdoch is the contact.
And his shop does a lot of the technical work for us.
But we're really trying to use the, quote, microcomputer to move on into the 20th century.
do some of this work.
Kent, by the way, is working with our prime in our college, and about as much as any student.
Aren't you the assistant to Terry?
I'm an assistant to Terry, and I've worked with the Army, utilizing the same kind of process, except with military installations instead of COGS.
Same type of process.
We're working on that.
We have, at the present time in our department now,
Times have changed, Leon.
We have four different types of microbes in our office.
And we're going to get a fifth.
In fact, we're getting two different.
We're going to end up with six different types of microbes in our department, beginning with crash 80s.
We wound up recognizing that there are so many different types of hardware floating around.
and so many different types of software and incompatibility and so forth.

We began trying to analyze where all the COGs were, and they did have different kinds of, you know, they had IBM PCs and they had, you know, some of them had IBM minis and, you know, on them different kinds of pieces of hardware.
But we just finally bit the bullet and purchased a TI.
We went out for bid and so forth, but we purchased
a TI professional computer with 256K and a dual floppy disk and some of that type stuff so that we now at least have a minimal level piece of equipment in each of the COGs.
And we can begin where our key use of that is going to be trying to develop our telecommunication network on our review process.
When we're reviewing applications for federal funds,
They're actually extensions of our office, and we're reviewing local projects.
They're going to be providing that information back to us about what's going through their organizations.
But we also see the micro as a first step to really an interactive communication between all 24 in our office on economic development.
Because I think, as we said about a year ago, economic development is going to be Mark White's
key concern in trying to deal with economic development matters.
He created a separate division of the governor's office.
Hardin-Wiedemann is now heading up.
And it's the key issue that he will deal with.
What brought about the change in the state planning officer?
Hardin used to be the state planning officer.
OK.

The key interest was that while we had that office called the Office of Planning and Intergovernmental Relations, we had about 20 person staff, 22 person or so, that while we had that organization and then we had the budget office, it was very clear that to really deal with economic development matters, there's going to have to be some dedicated staff, hardened
I don't know if you recall some of his background, but his background is tailored very well to economic development matters.
He's worked on an international scene.
He knows and speaks fluent French, German, I think, several different languages, and has actually developed, was working with the National Democratic Party
out of Washington and had a lot of fundraisers for the party.
So he's dealt in circles of the economic development industry.
Was he involved with his business in Dallas too?
He was involved in financial community in Dallas and things.
So he just had the background.
And we began trying to service Governor White out of that Office of Planning and Intergovernmental Relations.
that staff team really did the early work for getting MCC in Austin.
But what we found is that trying to deal with those kinds of issues, it took almost 100% of the time.
I mean, you could just chew up a lot of different man hours in that area and not really go on about the business of trying to go beyond that.
So Governor White
decided to create a separate division in the governor's office and add focus.
And so Hardin took that on.
What is Bob's background?
Bob McPherson started working in the governor's office, this governor's office, back in 1970 or 69.
Was involved in manpower planning at the time.
quite extensive interest, very strong interest in planning and background in planning business.
Worked with the Department of Labor for a while.
Worked in Seattle, I believe it was, and Washington State in the planning business there.
Private or public?
Publicly financed.
I'm not sure how it was structured.
I don't know if it was in a public agency.
I don't know if it was publicly financed.
Who was the Carter's laborer?
Ray Marshall.
Ray Marshall came back after the Carter administration ended over at University of Texas.
That's where he came from anyway, came back there.
And Bob became a key advisor to Ray Marshall over at the University of Texas.

And as Governor White came into office and began trying to establish, since manpower business was going through a great transition from the old CETA program to the Job Training Partnership Act, Bob was a key advisor to Marshall.
And so he became a key advisor to Governor White
sort of contractual basis to establish this new program in Texas.
And so we just moved on over really later full time.
And so Governor White has used him as a key advisor for job training.
And at the time all this transition was going on, Bob became sort of a natural to move into the director of planning job.
What is the status of state planning today?
Does the governor's office have a plan for planning or a strategy for planning?
Or what does the governor want done in terms of the state's role in planning Texas today?
That's one thing that I was hoping Bob could speak to.
And I hate to answer boring there.
We'll ask him, too.
We can compare notes and see if we believe the same thing.
We do want to create something that would be very, very important.
I think Governor White is very interested in reinstituting planning.
We look back and see that we've lost ground in a number of years.
We do feel that Like the Texas 2000 project was a valuable project to a certain extent.
It was truly a Blue Ribbon project type, Blue Ribbon committee type project, but really did not get involvement or citizens being involved in the process.
And Governor White is a much more citizen-oriented, people-oriented governor.

And while he appreciates and wants the views of influential people, I think this administration will look more toward, OK, now that's what these folks, under the 2000 project, that's what they thought.
Now let's go beyond.
2000, under its process, only dealt with about, I won't go back, but six or seven key issues, all oriented around the economy.
all oriented around energy, water, and key issues that were mostly those things that you must have, quote, and to deal with 2000.
There was no concern or there was no dealing with human service problems.
What will our needs be as far as the people?
What are our health problems?
There was a human service side was something totally left out.
I think Governor White has expressed interest in trying to make sure that our planning and our activity deals with people as well as the physical assets of the state.
There's only a certain amount of time left in his term of office before he has to stand for reelection or whatever.
I think Governor White is looking beyond a year and a half or so.
I think he probably feels that in order to lay good groundwork, it's going to take some time.
And I think that he believes that he's probably got six or seven more years to solve the state's problems.
He's certainly not dealing with things and saying that I only have a term of two years left.
There are key things that we're moving out on right now, but we're trying to, I think Bob will tell you that we're moving slowly.
We're trying to re-establish some of the basic premises that we had in the early years.
One effort right now that we have a policy paper out on that we might share with you, health planning is an issue that's been around since day one I entered and here we are back in
trying to restructure, quote, health planning in Texas.
And we have a paper that I think will begin showing you what we do believe as far as planning concepts.
There are some guidelines that we began establishing in there that I think you will find reflective of what we're trying to accomplish.
We're not going to have the blue ribbon, big splash committees that we deal with at the state level.
I think the efforts that we make, we're going to be trying to look at local involvement.
And we're going to be trying to deal with broad sectors of issues like health, like jobs.
We're going to be dealing with those.
Economic development obviously hardened
division down there.
They're going to have an economic development plan that's going to carve out a swatch.
You're talking about services, mainly, and a certain amount of analysis.

But it strikes me that the pendulum has swung completely to the opposite extreme from physical environmental planning, because you haven't mentioned that at all as part of the State Planning Office's expected realm of activities.
Am I wrong in assuming that the state has gotten completely away from that aspect of state planning?
Bob, I think the agenda is still open for, quote, the natural resource type planning, interagency planning activities.
Obviously, again, we've got the functional planning in each of our natural resource type agencies.
But with the end of TNRAC, that is a policy area that is not, on an interagency basis, it's not linked up.
It is an area that I think Governor White is ultimately going to have to shore up.
Is the staff here moving in that direction at all, in terms of making recommendations?
I think so.
It's just not as clear in that area right now as some of the other areas.
There's been pressures and other things that have forced us into several issues that we've got that we feel like it's very much on our plate.
Economic development does, to a great extent, pick up quite a few pieces.
But water, for example, is a key area.
that the governor right now is working with both sides of the legislature, with the Water Resources Department, and that area right there, it hits at the heart of the matter.

We've got the development types that want all the water that the state can use to develop our state, and you've got the environmentalists that say, hey, you've got to be concerned about aquifers and other problems.
So we've got
We've got that issue right before us.
But trying to create a council or trying to deal with a group that can really get a handle on that, that's still out.
I think the jury's still out there.
I do not think, I guess this is my staff perspective, I do not see Mark White creating a comprehensive planning
function to where it's all tied together in a neat little package.
I see him dealing with health.
I see him dealing with economic development.
I see him dealing with the whole arena of jobs and services for the poor and planning in that area.
Natural resources is one that we've got to deal with and will.
I feel very confident.
But trying then to overarch that is where I'm not sure where Governor White will .

I'm just wondering if, because we've been talking about the goals for Texas and how that did bring all these major concerns together, if that might not be a framework that you might take a look at in tying together the economic and the resource concerns and the human services concerns.
Well, goals for Texas were certainly an issue looked at early in the White administration because Ed Grisham became the governor's key program guy.
And he was, as I mentioned earlier, the lead person for Governor Smith under Dan Petty to do the old goals program.
So he very much favored that type effort.
That was certainly looked at.
I think the Texas 2000 project was looked at as a model.
And I think both of those.
are things that we will try to glean the pieces of.
But I do not see right now another Goldsboro program.
I do not see another Texas 2000.
But I think there are little pieces of those things that will be drawn together in an overall program.
I think Bob.
probably needs to also add to this, because he's done a lot of thinking in the area.
As director of planning now, it's certainly a concern that he's been toying with.
And he's been getting a lot of input from a lot of different folks.
And I think he'll be the first to say that we're trying to establish a complete planning program.
I think he wants to start slow.
He wants to try to make sure that the planning that's done is planning that will have results at the end.
I think he's very concerned about a paper shuffle planning process where it really doesn't pan out.
This is a good point, because if we have another award winning planning program,

that doesn't lead anywhere, and another Texas 2000 blue ribbon high pressure committee that doesn't seem to lead anywhere, then people are going to become very wary of programs that don't have any payoff.
And it's that sort of thing that I think that we as planners have to guard against.
And in that sense, I think Bob deserves a lot of support in being quite
cautious about moving ahead and making sure that what is done can be quite visible in terms of its payoff.
I think Bob is that type of person.
I think he studies and reviews.
And he's a person with depth.
And he looks at that.
And I think once he gets settled on where he wants to go, I think we'll see a very strong program.
But I think we're still in that.
Bob came on effectively around October 1 and began the process of trying to acclimate into that position.
And I think we've been trying to grow and understand the perspective of state government.
I think once we get rolling, it'll be a real strong program.
